      { q: 'Compared with A* (Exp. 6), potential fields are:',
        o: ['Globally optimal but slow', 'Fast and reactive but not globally complete', 'Identical', 'Only for arms'], a: 1,
        e: 'Potential fields are cheap local methods; they trade completeness for reactivity.' }
    ],
    '6': [
      { q: 'A* expands the open node with the smallest value of:',
        o: ['g only (cost so far)', 'h only (heuristic)', 'f = g + h', 'random'], a: 2,
        e: 'A* orders the frontier by f = g + h, balancing known cost and estimated remainder.' },
      { q: 'A* with the heuristic h = 0 everywhere becomes:',
        o: ['Greedy best-first', "Dijkstra's algorithm", 'Depth-first search', 'BFS on a weighted graph only by luck'], a: 1,
        e: 'With h=0, f=g, so A* expands by cost-so-far exactly like Dijkstra.' },
      { q: 'For A* to guarantee an optimal path, the heuristic must be:',
        o: ['As large as possible', 'Admissible (never overestimates)', 'Always zero', 'Equal to g'], a: 1,
        e: 'An admissible (never-overestimating) heuristic guarantees optimality.' },
      { q: 'On an 8-connected grid, the exact admissible distance metric is:',
        o: ['Manhattan', 'Octile', 'Chebyshev with diagonal cost 1', 'Hamming'], a: 1,
        e: 'Octile accounts for sqrt(2) diagonals exactly, so it is admissible and tight.' }
    ],
    '7': [
      { q: 'Increasing the proportional gain Kp alone typically:',
        o: ['Slows the rise and removes overshoot', 'Speeds the rise but increases overshoot', 'Has no effect', 'Only changes steady-state error sign'], a: 1,
        e: 'More Kp pushes harder for a given error: faster rise, but more overshoot/oscillation.' },
      { q: 'The derivative term Kd primarily provides:',
        o: ['Steady-state offset removal', 'Damping that reduces overshoot', 'Faster steady-state drift', 'Integral wind-up'], a: 1,
        e: 'Kd reacts to de/dt, opposing rapid motion and damping oscillation.' },
      { q: 'Persistent steady-state error is best removed by adding:',
        o: ['More Kp', 'Integral term Ki', 'More Kd', 'More mass'], a: 1,
        e: 'Ki integrates residual error until the offset is driven to zero.' },
      { q: 'Settling time (2% band) is the time for the response to:',
        o: ['First reach the setpoint', 'Enter and stay within 2% of the setpoint', 'Reach peak overshoot', 'Double its value'], a: 1,
        e: 'Settling time is when the output enters and remains inside the +/-2% band.' }
    ],
    '8': [
      { q: 'The upright equilibrium (theta = 0) of an inverted pendulum is:',
        o: ['Stable', 'Unstable', 'Marginally stable', 'Nonexistent'], a: 1,
        e: 'Any small deviation grows; without control the pole falls. It is open-loop unstable.' },
      { q: 'Which feedback term most directly rights a tilting pole?',
        o: ['kx (cart position)', 'k_theta (pole angle)', 'kv (cart velocity)', 'none'], a: 1,
        e: 'k_theta applies force proportional to tilt, generating the moment that uprights the pole.' },
      { q: 'The angular-rate gain k_omega in the controller acts to:',
        o: ['Center the cart', 'Damp the pole oscillation', 'Increase the tilt', 'Set the setpoint'], a: 1,
        e: 'k_omega opposes theta_dot, damping the swing so the pole settles upright.' },
      { q: 'The cart-position gains (kx, kv) are included so that:',
        o: ['The pole spins faster', 'The cart stays near center while balancing', 'The angle is ignored', 'The force is constant'], a: 1,
        e: 'Without them the cart could balance the pole while drifting off the track indefinitely.' }
    ],
    '9': [
      { q: 'The damped-least-squares step delta_q = J^T (J J^T + lambda^2 I)^-1 e is used instead of the pure pseudo-inverse to:',
        o: ['Make the arm move faster', 'Stay well-behaved (bounded) near singularities', 'Guarantee a closed-form solution', 'Remove the need for a Jacobian'], a: 1,
        e: 'The lambda^2 I term keeps (J J^T + lambda^2 I) invertible, so joint velocities stay bounded where J loses rank.' },
      { q: 'A column of the planar position Jacobian for joint j is geometrically:',
        o: ['The link length L_j', 'The vector from joint j to the tip rotated 90 degrees', 'Always the unit x-axis', 'The joint angle theta_j'], a: 1,
        e: 'Rotating a revolute joint sweeps the tip perpendicular to the joint-to-tip vector, so the column is that vector rotated 90 deg.' },
      { q: 'At a singular configuration the manipulability w = sqrt(det(J J^T)):',
        o: ['Goes to infinity', 'Approaches zero (ellipse collapses to a line)', 'Equals the number of links', 'Is undefined'], a: 1,
        e: 'A singularity means a singular value of J hits zero, so det(J J^T) -> 0 and the manipulability ellipse flattens.' },
      { q: 'For a 3-link arm doing a 2-D positioning task, the IK problem is:',
